Children's cold and cough medicines are under scrutiny by federal regulators due to insufficient testing in children.
Pediatricians warn against overdosing, as some children have experienced adverse effects even with recommended doses.
The FDA advises against using these medications for children under 2 without a doctor's approval.
Major manufacturers voluntarily recalled infant cough and cold products to prevent misuse.
Safety experts suggest banning over-the-counter cough and cold medicines for children under 6 due to limited effectiveness and potential dangers.
The FDA is reviewing the safety and effectiveness of these products for young children.
